<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-09-17T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-09-17T21:00:00-05:00" n="616" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d616">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/3195: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-09-18T10:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">September 18,
                                        1923—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received September 18—5:17
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>315. Asiatic News Agency telegraphs following from Mukden published in
                                <hi rend="italic">Peking Leader</hi> of today: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“As a result of Doctor Schurman’s visit to Mukden and Harbin,
                                    General Chang Tso-lin has issued instructions to General Chu
                                    Chin-Ian, chief of the zone of the Chinese Eastern Railway,
                                    ordering the postponement of the taking over of the land
                                    department until the problem has been fully discussed by the
                                    members of the board of directors of the Chinese Eastern
                                    Railway, the foreign consuls and the Chinese authorities.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>